author: alchion

comments.content:
Looks _almost_ like [Optima](http://web.archive.org/web/20081119131235/http:/www.myfonts.com/fonts/linotype/optima/) to me, but not quite.

Very tightly kerned, regardless.

I thought of a partially de-serifed version of [Americana](http://web.archive.org/web/20081119131235/http:/www.fontshop.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=catalog.fontdetail&displayfontid=EF.100992.0.1&attributes.sampleSize=48&sampleText=Windermere&sampleSize=32). (With extremely tight tracking).

- Mike Yanega

Close too is OL Radiant Light

[http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/ortizlopez/olradiant/light/testdrive.html](http://web.archive.org/web/20081119131235/http:/www.myfonts.com/fonts/ortizlopez/olradiant/light/testdrive.html "http://www.myfonts.com/fonts/ortizlopez/olradiant/light/testdrive.html")
If I had my PLINC book I bet I would see it in there. Awful spacing on that logo, huh? I think it’s a photo type from the 70’s, not something else customized.

I think Patty’s right — at least that’s the closest we’ve seen. (I looked through my three PhotoLettering catalogs and didn’t see a better match).

- Mike Yanega
For anyone with a VGC catalog, it looks alot like Baker Sans - either Display Regular or Fineline Regular.
